{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503405"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:00:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:00:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2027"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2027"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.04,0.01,0.75,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2027"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92940"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2027"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2027"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76293"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1481"},{"type":"tags","id":"1947"},{"type":"tags","id":"2806"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13166"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31899"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92940"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of back stiffness and pain. He has also noticed eye pain and blurred vision. There have been no changes to his bowel or bladder habits, and he denies a history of intravenous drug use. He has a medical history of asthma diagnosed last year for which he takes regular budesonide/formoterol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A diastolic decrescendo murmur is present, loudest at the left lower sternal edge.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ehlers Danlos syndrome","Aortic dissection","Vertebral compression fracture","Ankylosing spondylitis","Sacroiliac joint infection"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eankylosing spondylitis\u003C/strong\u003E. This chronic inflammatory condition typically presents in young adults (15-30 years old) with insidious onset of low back pain and stiffness lasting more than three months. The patient\u0027s age, duration of symptoms, and pattern of back pain are consistent with this diagnosis. Two key extra-articular manifestations support the diagnosis of ankylosing spondylitis in this case. First, the eye symptoms (pain and blurred vision) suggest anterior uveitis. Second, the diastolic decrescendo murmur at the left lower sternal edge is consistent with aortic regurgitation, a known cardiovascular complication of ankylosing spondylitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEhlers Danlos syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a group of inherited connective tissue disorders characterised by joint hypermobility, skin hyperextensibility, and tissue fragility. While it can cause joint pain, it does not typically present with the inflammatory back pain described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic dissection\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden, severe chest or back pain, often described as tearing or ripping. It is more common in older individuals with risk factors such as hypertension. The chronic nature of this patient\u0027s symptoms makes aortic dissection unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVertebral compression fractures\u003C/strong\u003E are more common in older individuals with osteoporosis or those with a history of trauma. The patient would be unlikely to sustain a osteoporotic vertebral fracture following only one-year of \u003Cem\u003Einhaled\u003C/em\u003E steroid use. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESacroiliac joint infection\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with acute onset of severe pain localised to the sacroiliac region, often accompanied by fever and other signs of infection. The chronic nature of the symptoms and lack of systemic signs of infection make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ankylosing spondylitis typically presents with inflammatory back pain, and can also present with other manifestations such as anterior uveitis and aortic regurgitation."],"references":["Practitioners TRAC of general. Ankylosing spondylitis [Internet]. Australian Family Physician. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/november/ankylosing-spondylitis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76293"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2027"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76293"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-20T09:10:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-20T09:10:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2027"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92940"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","n